    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Thanks. So if the city finds an undocumented encroachment—meaning it wasn't part of the original permit—does that usually trigger an enforcement action or an order to vacate the space? I'm worried about how the city handles \"squatting\" on those non-conforming setbacks during inspections.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Undocumented encroachments, or unpermitted structures, are generally treated as violations, which can trigger enforcement actions from the city's code compliance department. The city can issue citations, fines, and, ultimately, an order to abate or remove the illegal structure to bring it into compliance with current zoning. It's best to address this immediately; proactively seeking a variance or correction is always preferable to waiting for an official inspection to uncover the issue.",
      "source": "target",
